GalGael 2014: be part of carving out the next chapter!On the face of it, GalGael work with people whose lives have been battered by homelessness, addiction and depression. Walk through the door of our workshop and you’ll find purposeful creativity and something beyond a strong sense of community. At our workbenches, skills and self-belief are built. Everywhere hands-on work creates hope and worth. Our methods are simple and effective but time and again we see folk fall. The pressure of life beyond the walls of the safe harbour we’ve created is too great. That’s why we understand our work as being more than with individuals. The issues they may arrive with - are the product of a society that’s off course – more than an indication they’ve somehow failed. Too many apparent solutions deal only with symptoms. Too many have been left high and dry by post-industrial realities of individualism and transaction. Roots are being lost and values blurred. At GalGael, we have created a cultural anchor point around which people are re-kindling skills, community and new narratives for the future. It’s brought us to the conclusion that it is not only people who need retraining but no less than society itself that needs re-worked. This thinking is at the cutting edge of our work. It’s a tall task and we don’t plan on doing it alone. We need the backing of like-minded individuals like you. With your help - we’re forging ahead with some bold ideas.Just as our story wouldn’t be possible without the thousands of folk who’ve helped write it so far, we need support from people like you to help us write the next chapter. Your contribution will help GalGael to grow its unique form of social innovation around positive learning experiences anchored in practical activities that offer connection and meaning.These new approaches are already starting to deliver results and rewrite life stories and in the past 6 months; 
5 people have gone into employment; 
3 in traditional crafts; 
11 people have become volunteers; 
5 have enrolled in further education;
and 45 who have taken part in our Journey On programme.
Your contributions will help us carve out the next chapter of GalGael’s work. Part of that is creating a workplace that challenges, inspires and creates the conditions for the individuals we work with to carve out their next chapter, which sometimes is leaving behind life stories that have been marked by isolation, and the kind of bankruptcy of hope that lead to addiction. As one of our people put it; “This is the first place has felt safe, GalGael. My head never stops but this helps make it more bearable.” For many of our people experiencing progressively harsh benefits cuts, we are the difference between hope and hardship. People who have been made to feel they have no part to play in society - their confidence stripped by countless structures. In that sense, we don’t see ourselves as a charity, but more a community of creative people, who come together to co-operatively meet some of our needs; our shared need for acceptance, to learn and contribute our creativity. Come down and see for yourself.As our founder Colin Macleod said; “It’s not enough to have the great dream. We’re interested in people who want to wrestle it into reality and that means getting your sleeves rolled up and dealing with the rough as well as the smooth...” We’ve been rolling our sleeves up for the last 17 years. There have been some rough times but it’s been worth it and all that hard graft is paying off. You can read more on our website about our work that continues to push boundaries and is increasingly gaining recognition. Our work spans the best part of two decades and reads a bit like a story. It’s woven with the human stories of those who’ve worked with us over that time - adding depth and life that make that story what it is. Some of our work is about re-writing old, limiting stories; both personal and societal. Dr. Sandra Carlisle of the Afternow Project explains it like this; “Where it differs from virtually all other such organisations – making it probably unique – is in providing a different kind of ‘story’ by which to live and with which to think, and thus a different kind of purpose and meaning in life. This strength should not be underestimated, even if it might not be readily understood by outsiders to the project. The meanings and values that GalGael participants bring to their work differ sharply from those found in mainstream society, where the dominant social and cultural values appear to be economism, individualism, consumerism and materialism.”GalGael offers day-in day-out a lived example of a different way for being in the world. It's not rocket science. Much of it is common sense. Our innovative model of work supports self-reliance among our participants, many of who are creating their own work because neither jobs nor benefits are readily available. The beauty of this model lies in that it does so at the same time as generating self-reliance for GalGael as a whole. But we still need wider support from people like you to ensure the continuation of our work. Your contribution will help make that happen. And if a contribution's not something you can offer right now, you can contribute by helping us get this campaign out there by sending it on to friends and family.

Summary
The disAbility News Reporter was created to give people with disabilities a voice and a professional news outlet. Our mission is to report current events within the context of the disability community. Our goal is to inform readers, both with and without disabilities, about how events and public policies impact the lives of people with disabilities and their families. We will cover a wide range of topics and fields to help our readers gain deeper insight into the disability community from the perspectives of those within it. Almost all of our writers are individuals with disabilities who have lived and worked within the community.  
Description of Campaign
In recent years the disability community has severely suffered under the weight of the American economic recession. However, many of its impacts are going unreported. For the disability community and its leaders to prosper, the disability community and those that wish to help out must have access to consistent news and an understanding of the issues that are impacting the community. By having access to disability news, discussions can take place, solutions can start to take form and actions can create better outcomes for the disability community. The positive social impact of disability news can be measured in terms of more employment opportunities, greater access to higher education, an increase in affordable and accessible housing, greater political involvement, and new ideas to solving problems.
Capital Goal
Our goal is to raise $55k by next year (but $15k by the end of this year) to fund our news operations. Currently, we are an unfunded initiative without paid staff. We function through in-kind donations from staff and guest writers. Your contributions will allow us to: 

Maintain and upgrade our website ($2k);
Upgrade our computer equipment (1 used laptop at $500) and software ( Dreamweaver CS6- web design packet at $500);
Open and sign a two-year lease for physical office space (one or two office rooms at $9k);
Hire one full-time staff member (writer) to contribute weekly news ($31k);
Hire one part-time staff member (administrative staff at $7k);
Buy subscription to Constant Contact (internet marketing tool at $200);
Pay for the incorporated of the disAbility News Reporter ($800 State fee);
Hire internet marketing consultants to help promote the website ($1.5k);
Pay for professional writing development workshops ($500); 
Sponsor two contests (writing news contest and a disability news comedy video contest ) to promote the website ($1k);
Purchased used office furniture ($500); and
Two years of utilities ($500).
Other Ways You Can Help


Follow us. Join our mailing list, follow us on Youtube, Twitter, Facebook, and use Indiegogo share tools.

Tell others about us. We think it is great that people, with and without disabilities, visit our website and read our news. Access to news from disability community members is a unique and interesting point of view that fosters positive social action and leads to a better community.

Offer free services or materials. In-kind and pro-bono support is need and appreciated. We will be taking advantage of many of the free services and low-cost workshops offered at the local Small Business Association. If you are Chicago-based internet marketing consultants we would love to meet with you. Please send us an email.      
About Our Founder
Jose Mendez is the founder of disAbility News Reporter. He has extensive work experience in the workforce development field with emphases on serving people with disabilities and low-income individuals, as well as other employment barriers. He has worked at several disability community and governmental organizations, including Access Living and the Mayor's Office of People with Disabilities in Chicago. Jose has also served on a number of disability-related boards and committees, such as the Illinois Statewide Independent Living Centers Council, the Mayor's Special Education Task Force, and the Committee for the Integration of Latinos with Disabilities. He has a Master’s Degree in Special Education from the University of Illinois at Chicago and was born with cerebral palsy.
